<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Load</h1>

<p>This notebook is made to understand how to predict the total load in italy. We basically start from some exploratory analysis and then we will look for the optimal model, after that we will implement that model into python.</p>

<h3 id="linear-regression">Linear Regression</h3>
</blockquote>
<pre class="r"><code class="hljs">set.seed(<span class="hljs-number">42</span>)
r &lt;- sample(nrow(load), nrow(load)*<span class="hljs-number">0.33</span>)
train &lt;- load[-r,]
test_x &lt;- load[r,-<span class="hljs-number">1</span>]
test_y &lt;- load[r,<span class="hljs-number">1</span>]
reg1 &lt;- glm(Load ~ ., data=train)
(summary(reg1))</code></pre>

<blockquote>
<h3 id="linear-regression-with-interaction-terms">Linear Regression with interaction terms:</h3>
</blockquote>
<pre class="r"><code class="hljs">reg2 &lt;- glm(Load ~ Month*Hours+Holiday, data=train)</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>MSE:</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code class="hljs">pred &lt;- predict(reg2, test_x)
MSE_LM_interaction &lt;- mean((test_y-pred)^<span class="hljs-number">2</span>)
print(MSE_LM_interaction)</code></pre>
<pre><code class="hljs">## [1] 13928483</code></pre>
<blockquote>
<h3 id="randomforest">RandomForest</h3>
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>Since the problems is non linear we will use models that perform better in this situation as the randomForest!</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code class="hljs"><span class="hljs-keyword">library</span>(randomForest)
MSE_randomForest &lt;- c()
forest &lt;- randomForest(Load~., data=train, ntree=<span class="hljs-number">250</span>, mtry=<span class="hljs-number">2</span>)
pred_forest &lt;- predict(forest, test_x)
MSE_Forest &lt;- mean((test_y-pred_forest)^<span class="hljs-number">2</span>)
MSE_randomForest &lt;- append(MSE_randomForest, MSE_Forest)
print(MSE_randomForest)</code></pre>
<pre><code class="hljs">## [1] 9903950</code></pre>
<blockquote>
<h3 id="comparision-of-the-models">Comparision of the models:</h3>
</blockquote>
<pre class="r"><code class="hljs">tmp &lt;- data.frame(MSE= c(MSE_LM_interaction, MSE_LM, min(MSE_randomForest)),
                  Model = c(<span class="hljs-string">'Linear_with_interaction'</span>, <span class="hljs-string">'Linear'</span>, <span class="hljs-string">'RandomForest'</span>))
ggplot(data=tmp, aes(x=Model, y=MSE, fill=MSE))+
  geom_histogram(stat=<span class="hljs-string">"identity"</span>)+ theme_tufte()+ggtitle(<span class="hljs-string">"MSE ~ Models"</span>)+
  theme(legend.position=<span class="hljs-string">"none"</span>)</code></pre>
